AB  - Ferroelectric tunnel junction (FTJ) has attracted great attentions in storage memory and neuromorphic computation applications due to its distinctive advantages such as non-destructive readout, fast write/read speed, and low power consumption. Many experiments and theoretical studies of FTJ have been developed since it was firstly proposed as "polar switch" by Esaki et al. in the 1971s [1]. Typical structure of FTJ is composed of a thin ferroelectric layer sandwiched between two metal electrodes. The main characteristic of FTJ is tunneling electro-resistance effect (TER), which is related to the change in the tunneling current as a result of polarization reversal. Various modifications such as replacing the electrode with the material of different screen length or introducing an interfacial dielectric layer between the ferroelectric layer and electrodes, are made to enhance the TER effect of FTJ. Thus, the structure of FTJ has gone through MFM, MFS, MFIM, and MFIS/MIFS, where M, F, I and S represent metal, ferroelectric, insulator and semiconductor, respectively. On the other hand, the material type and thickness of ferroelectric layer have great impact on the properties of FTJ. The ferroelectricity of ferroelectric layer is suppressed with the decrease of the thickness, which lead to low TER ratio (= I ON /I OF F). Besides, the traditional ferroelectric layer of FTJ is mainly based on perovskites, which are not compatible with the CMOS processand not easily scaled. Recently, it was discovered that the doped-HfO 2 like Zirconium (Zr) doped HfO 2 (HZO) shows robust ferroelectricity, excellent scalability and compatibility [2]. A newly published experimental work demonstrates that the FTJ with ultra-thin 1 nm ferroelectric layer still has enhanced ferroelectricity, which provides the solution to the above problems [3]. In this paper, the double barrier FTJ are theoretically studied and simulated by two methods. Method I is a 1st order approximation which calculates the tunneling current by solving the Poisson's equation and Tsu-Esaki equation with Wentzel-Kramers-Brillouin (WKB) methodin one-step. Method II is a self-consistent solution of the coupled Poisson's equation and current continuity equation, in which the carrier generation rate calculated from the tunneling current is introduced. Simulation results of the two methods are consistent with the experimental results of others. What's more, as the ferroelectric layer thickness, barrier height or carrier mobility decreases to the extent that the tunneling carriers significantly affect thecarrier distribution in semiconductor through diffusive transport, method I is not valid and method II is required.
