AB  - As one of the thinnest forms of semiconducting silicon, monolayer (ML) silicane has not only excellent gate electrostatics and carrier transport ability, but also compatibility with well-established silicon-based technology. We explore the device performance limits of sub-5-nm ML silicane metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect transistors (MOSFETs) by applying ab initio quantum transport simulations. The on-state current, effective delay time, and power-delay product of the optimized n-type and p-type ML silicane MOSFETs can well or nearly meet the high-performance device requirements of the International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors (ITRS) at a gate length of 5 nm. Those of the optimized n-type ML silicane MOSFETs at a gate length of 3 nm and the p-type ML silicane MOSFETs at a gate length of 5 nm can meet the low-power-device demands of the ITRS. Thus, ML silicane as channel materials can scale the Moore's law down to 5 nm.
